In TypeScript, classes and interfaces cannot currently be declared to implement union types.  It has been [suggested](https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/11207), but nothing has happened there yet.  So there&#39;s no easy way for the compiler to understand that `MyClass extends MyType` is true.

The two ways I can think of to deal with this involve refactoring your code.  If an instance of `MyClass` is likely to switch back and forth between the two types of `MyType` (e.g., first it&#39;s `{isSet: false, id: null}`, and then later it&#39;s `{isSet: true, id: 123}`), then I&#39;d recommend making `MyClass` *have* a `MyType` instead of *be* a `MyType`.  This is sort of [composition over inheritance](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Composition_over_inheritance).  Here&#39;s how I&#39;d do that:

    class MyClass {
        myType: MyType = { isSet: false, id: null };

        constructor(id?: number) {
            if (typeof id === &#39;number&#39; &amp;&amp; id &gt; 0) {
                this.myType = { isSet: true, id };
            }
        }

        test() {
            if (this.myType.isSet) {
                this.logId(this.myType.id);
            }
        }
        logId(id: number) {
            console.log(id);
        }
    }

Note that all references to `this.isSet` or `this.id` were replaced with `this.myType.isSet` and `this.myType.id`.

And you can test it:

    const s = new MyClass(123);
    s.test(); // 123
    const u = new MyClass();
    u.test(); // nothing


---

The other way I&#39;d do it satisfies your original idea that `MyClass` instances actually *are* `MyType`s, but it only works if individual `MyClass` instances will always be either one or the other member of the `MyType` union and do not change.  In this case you can get `MyClass` to be a union of two related classes, like this:

    abstract class MyClassBase {
        abstract isSet: boolean;
        abstract id: number | null;
        abstract test(): void;
        logId(id: number) {
            console.log(id);
        }
    }

    class MyClassSet extends MyClassBase implements Extract&lt;MyType, { isSet: true }&gt;{
        readonly isSet = true;
        readonly id: number;
        constructor(id: number) {
            super();
            this.id = id;
        }
        test() {
            this.logId(this.id);
        }
    }

    class MyClassUnset extends MyClassBase implements Extract&lt;MyType, { isSet: false }&gt; {
        readonly isSet = false;
        readonly id = null;
        constructor() {
            super();
        }
        test() { }
    }

    type MyClass = MyClassSet | MyClassUnset;
    const MyClass = class {
        constructor(id?: number) {
            return (typeof id === &#39;number&#39; &amp;&amp; id &gt; 0) ?
                new MyClassSet(id) : new MyClassUnset();
        }
    } as new (id?: number) =&gt; MyClass;

So both `MyClassSet` and `MyClassUnset` are subclasses of `MyClassBase`, an abstract class in which you&#39;d put all common functionality.  If you need to specify `this: MyType` in method parameters there, it should be fine to do it.  But you probably shouldn&#39;t, since any functionality which differs based on whether it&#39;s set or unset should be implemented in the corresponding subclass.

Then the `MyClass` type is the union of `MyClassSet` and `MyClassUnset`, and you can even make a `MyClass` constructor that returns a `MyClass`.  

The test behaves the same as before:

    const s = new MyClass(123);
    s.test(); // 123
    const u = new MyClass();
    u.test(); // nothing

----

I&#39;d usually prefer the first solution where `MyClass` holds a property of type `MyType` instead of tries to implement `MyType`, because it&#39;s more straightforward.  But sometimes class hierarchies are useful, too.  

Okay, hope that helps; good luck!

