I&#39;m seeing several issues with this code. The first issue is that you appear to have confused an array and an object.

An object is essentially a map to where data is located. It has two components: keys and attributes. Your &#39;testArray&#39; is an object, and will not behave as an array. Your keys are all numbers, and the way you&#39;ve written the array, it won&#39;t compile. You would need to make your keys into strings `var testArray = ({&#39;30&#39;: &#39;hello everyone&#39;})` or you would need to write out a key that starts with a letter. `var testArray = ({thirty: &#39;hello everyone&#39;})`

An array would be declared with square brackets, and would be something like this:

    var myArray = [&quot;hello everyone&#39;,&#39;i hope&#39;,&#39;you all&#39;,&#39;are&#39;,&#39;fine&#39;]

An array is just a list of data. Each element has something called in index, which starts at 0, and tells us where an element is in an array. In this example, &#39;hello everyone&#39; is at index 0. &#39;i hope&#39; is at index 1, &#39;you all&#39; is at index 2, etc. You can use the index of an array to return the element that you want. If I write out

    console.log(myArray[3]) //&#39;are&#39;

I will receive the string &#39;are&#39;, because it is the third element of the array. I can also use this technique to re-assign values in an array.

    myArray[4] = &#39;excellent&#39;
    console.log(myArray) // &#39;hello everyone&#39;,&#39;i hope&#39;,&#39;you all&#39;,&#39;are&#39;,&#39;doing&#39;,&#39;excellent&#39;

For what you&#39;re looking to do, it sounds like you should use a helper variable to swap values between array indexes. Example:

    let helperVar = myArray[2]
    Array[2] = myArray[5]
    myArray[5] = helperVar
    console.log(myArray)
    // &#39;hello everyone&#39;,&#39;i hope&#39;,&#39;fine&#39;,&#39;are&#39;,&#39;you all&#39;

First of all, that is not an array that is an Object. If you want to keep the object, you have to transform it into an array

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var testArray = ({ 30 : &#39;hello everyone&#39;, 31 : &#39;i hope&#39;, 32 : &#39;you all&#39;, 33 : &#39;are&#39;, 34 : &#39;fine&#39;, });
    var tempArray = Object.values(testArray)
    var newArray = tempArray.sort(() =&gt; Math.random() - 0.5);
    console.log(newArray)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

If you want to keep the keys you can change your object to an array of object

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var testArray = ([{ 30 : &#39;hello everyone&#39;}, {31 : &#39;i hope&#39;},{ 32 : &#39;you all&#39;}, {33 : &#39;are&#39;}, {34 : &#39;fine&#39;}]);
    var newArray = testArray.sort(() =&gt; Math.random() - 0.5);
    console.log(newArray)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

